and on the reception and recycling of Brecht in India, respectively. Other papers are on a wide range of topics, from Brecht's own "recycling" of Shakespeare and others, through the reception of his own works in a range of contexts and by later writers, to contemporary works that may be understood as post-Brechtian. The final section, introduced by an extended interview with American playwright Tony Kushner, documents additional creative responses to the theme.Volume co-editors Tom Kuhn and David Barnett are, respectively, Professor of Twentieth-Century German Literature at the University of Oxford and Professor of Theatre at the University of York. Managing Editor Theodore F. Rippey is Associate Professor of German at Bowling Green State University.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 4aFilm & Theatre. 4aGerman Literature. 7aDRAMA / European / German.2bisacsh  aBrecht Yearbook.  aBrecht reception.  aBrecht symposium.  aBrecht's works.  aBrechtian approaches.  aDas Brecht-Jahrbuch 42.  aInternational Brecht Society.  aRecycling Brecht.  aliterary analysis.  aliterary theory.  apost-Brechtian.  atheater analysis.  atheater studies.1 aAllana, Amal, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarnett, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarnett, David, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBeloff, Zoe, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrady, Martin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrockmann, Stephen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBromander, Henrik, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDiekmann, Stefanie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGi